d in 1908.<ref name="AOC">{{cite web|title=Helen Keller|url=https://www.aoc.gov/art/national-statuary-hall-collection/helen-keller|publisher=[[Architect of the Capitol]]|accessdate=December 30, 2017}}</ref>
==Description and history== On October 7, 2009, a bronze statue of Keller was added to the [[National Statuary Hall Collection]], as a replacement for the State of Alabama's former 1908 statue of the education reformer [[Jabez Lamar Monroe Curry]]. It is displayed in the [[United States Capitol Visitor Center]] and depicts Keller as a seven-year-old child standing at a [[Hand pump|water pump]]. The statue represents the seminal moment in Keller's life when she understood her first word: W-A-T-E-R, as signed into her hand by teacher Anne Sullivan. The pedestal base bears a quotation in raised Latin and braille letters: "The best and most beautiful things in the world cannot be seen or even touched, they must be felt with the heart."<ref name=AOC/> The statue is the first one of a person with a disability and of a child to be permanently displayed at the [[United States Capitol|U.S. Capitol]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Helen Keller Statue Unveiled in Capitol |newspaper=[[CBS News]] |date=October 7, 2009 |url=http://www.cbsnews.com/stories/2009/10/07/politics/main5369775.shtml |accessdate=December 25, 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| title=Helen Keller statue unveiled at Capitol |newspaper=[[CNN]] |date=October 7, 2009 |url=http://www.cnn.com/2009/US/10/07/HELEN.KELLER.STATUE/index.html |accessdate=December 25, 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=One Impressive Kid Gets Her Statue at Capitol |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |date=October 8, 2009 |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2009/10/07/AR2009100703498.html |accessdate=December 25, 2008 }}</ref>
